    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                  <jats:p>People may create or seek out performance‐inhibiting obstacles to avoid negative feedback about their ability. This behavior, called self‐handicapping, allows agents to attribute failures to self‐imposed obstacles rather than to lack of competence. I model rational agents with preferences for maintaining self‐esteem, and provide sufficient conditions under which they engage in rational self‐handicapping behavior. I consider two policy applications: education and tournaments. Exams with noisier questions strictly increase studying. Policies encouraging particular groups to apply for jobs can result in strategic adjustment, decreasing applications from the targeted group.</jats:p>",
